Author-Name: Anna Scherbina 
Author-Workplace-Name: Harvard Business School 
Title: Differences of Opinion and the Cross Section of Stock Returns 
Abstract:
 We provide evidence that stocks with higher dispersion in analysts'
 earnings forecasts earn lower future returns than otherwise similar
 stocks. This effect is most pronounced in small stocks and stocks that
 have performed poorly over the past year. Interpreting dispersion in
 analysts' forecasts as a proxy for differences in opinion about a stock,
 we show that this evidence is consistent with the hypothesis that prices
 will reflect the optimistic view whenever investors with the lowest
 valuations do not trade. By contrast, our evidence is inconsistent with a
 view that dispersion in analysts' forecasts proxies for risk. Copyright The American Finance Association 2002. 
