Author-Name: David M. Reeb 
Author-Workplace-Name: Culverhouse College of Commerce, University of Alabama 
Title: Corporate Diversification: What Gets Discounted? 
Abstract:
 Prior literature finds that diversified firms sell at a discount relative
 to the sum of the imputed values of their business segments. We explore
 this documented discount and argue that it stems from risk-reducing
 effects of corporate diversification. Consistent with this risk-reduction
 hypothesis, we find that (a) shareholder losses in diversification are a
 function of firm leverage, (b) all equity firms do not exhibit a
 diversification discount, and (c) using book values of debt to compute
 excess value creates a downward bias for diversified firms. Overall, the
 results indicate that diversification is insignificantly related to excess
 firm value. Copyright The American Finance Association 2002. 
